<!-- This article was automatically created by [[User:polbot]] from http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=E000219. The prose may be stilted, and there may be grammatical and Wikification errors. Please improve in any way you see fit. -->'''Frederick Essen''' ([[April 22]], [[1863]] - [[August 18]], [[1946]]) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Missouri]].

Born near Pond, St. Louis County, Missouri, Essen attended the public schools.
He engaged in agricultural pursuits.
<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->Recorder of deeds of St. Louis County 1894-1902.
He engaged in newspaper business at [[Clayton, Missouri]], becoming the owner of two papers which he combined under the name of the Watchman-Advocate.
He served as delegate to the Republican National Conventions in 1904, 1908, and 1912.
He served as member of the board of education of Clayton and served as president 1909-1919.

Essen was elected as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the Sixty-fifth Congress to fill the vacancy caused by the death of Jacob E. Meeker and served from [[November 5]], [[1918]], until [[March 3]], [[1919]].
He was not a candidate for renomination in 1918.
He resumed newspaper activities.
He was also interested in banking.
He died in [[Creve Coeur, Missouri]], [[August 18]], [[1946]].
He was interred in Bethel Cemetery, [[Pond, Missouri]].

